In .NET 10 MAUI, Android defaults to **edge-to-edge** rendering, which means `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` (what `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` mapped to) no longer drives layout changes. The replacement is **`WindowInsets`** — you react to the IME (keyboard) inset and add bottom padding yourself.

### Quick fix — handle insets in `MainActivity.cs`

```csharp
// Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;

public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity
{
    protected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)
    {
        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

        // Keep adjustResize as a hint (still partially respected)
        Window!.SetSoftInputMode(SoftInput.AdjustResize);

        // React to keyboard insets for edge-to-edge
        var content = FindViewById(Android.Resource.Id.Content)!;
        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(content, new InsetsListener());
    }

    private class InsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

            // Use the larger of keyboard or nav-bar bottom inset
            int bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom);
            v.SetPadding(0, 0, 0, bottom);

            return insets;
        }
    }
}
```

### Why this works

| Concept | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Edge-to-edge** | .NET 10 MAUI draws behind system bars; your layout must account for insets manually. |
| **`Ime()` inset** | Represents the keyboard height in pixels. When the keyboard is hidden it's `0`. |
| **`NavigationBars()`** | Ensures the input bar still clears the gesture/nav bar when the keyboard is closed. |

### Also make sure

1. **AndroidManifest.xml** still has `android:windowSoftInputMode="adjustResize"` on the `<activity>` — it tells the system to dispatch IME insets.
2. Your input bar is at the **bottom of the page layout** (e.g., in a `Grid` row with `RowDefinition="Auto"`), so the padding push actually moves it up.

This replaces the old one-liner and works reliably on Android 15+ with edge-to-edge.
